1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,240
All right, so there are only two types of cryptography that exist, Symmetric and Asymmetric.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:40,000
All right, so there are only two types of cryptography that exist, Symmetric and Asymmetric.

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
And if you look those up in a dictionary, if you look up the word Symmetric in a dictionary, for example,

4
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
it's going to say the same. And obviously what they're talking about is the key.

5
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:58,000
The same key has to be at both ends for sender and receiver to be able to communicate with each other.

6
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:01,000
That's what we refer to as Symmetric key cryptography.

7
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Asymmetric, on the other hand, means not the same.

8
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Therefore, we have different keys that encrypt and decrypt at both ends.

9
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
But for now, we're going to talk about Symmetric key cryptography.

10
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:20,000
And one of the things that I think we need to always remember is that the advantage of Symmetric key cryptography,

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
it's going to be that it's very fast. That's its biggest advantage.

12
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:32,000
And for what companies do today, and what we need to do across, for example, untrusted networks,

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,000
we have a lot of data that may need to be encrypted and decrypted.

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Symmetric key cryptography is really the only solution that we can use.

15
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,000
But then again, the problem that we have with this is called key distribution.

16
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:52,000
How do we securely distribute the key to the other end without having anybody in between

17
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:59,000
to know what that key is, which is a fundamental problem associated with Symmetric key cryptography?

18
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:05,000
And so when we look at the Symmetric key cryptography method itself,

19
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:10,000
there are some key advantages and disadvantages that we need to think about.

20
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Of course, the biggest advantage is speed.

21
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:18,000
In fact, it can encrypt to the tune of hundreds of millions of bits per second.

22
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
That's how fast these algorithms actually are.

23
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
And if we're using some algorithms that support large or long key lengths,

24
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:30,000
then obviously these end up very strong algorithms.

25
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Now, the disadvantages are, and what you see in yellow here is what we need to keep in mind

26
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,000
and always focus on.

27
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:43,000
The biggest disadvantage of Symmetric key cryptography is the problem of key distribution.

28
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Now, that's part of what we call key management.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
We're going to focus on key management issues later on.

30
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:56,000
But for now, the biggest part of key management issue that is associated with Symmetric key cryptography

31
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:59,000
is the key distribution problem.

32
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:05,000
There is a secondary problem that we also need to think about, and that is scalability.

33
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:10,000
It does not scale well as you start adding more people, for example,

34
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
that need to be involved in secure communications.

35
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:19,000
And the way that you figure this out is that if you have two people, for example,

36
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:24,000
that need to communicate securely with each other, there's one key that's required,

37
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:32,000
as long as the sender and receiver have the same key, then those two people can communicate securely with each other.

38
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:38,000
But the problem is, as you start adding more people, you need to add more keys.

39
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:42,000
And in fact, the number of keys required starts growing exponentially.

40
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:48,000
For example, if we have three people in a group that need to communicate securely with each other,

41
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:55,000
the number of keys required now for each of those people to communicate securely with each other is three.

42
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:01,000
And if you go to four people, for example, the number of keys that are required actually grows to six.

43
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:09,000
From this point on, every time you add one more person, it actually doubles the number of keys that are required.

44
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:16,000
So it's growing exponentially. So if you had ten people that needed to securely communicate with each other,

45
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:19,000
the number of keys required would be forty-five.

46
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:23,000
And if you bring that number up to a thousand people, for example,

47
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:30,000
all of a sudden we need almost five hundred thousand keys that need to be securely managed, for example,

48
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:35,000
in that system that allows those people to communicate securely with each other.

49
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:42,000
So this type of cryptography, even though it has some really good advantages, doesn't scale very well.

50
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
And that's the secondary problem that it also has as far as a disadvantageous concern.

51
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:54,000
So for now, just remember the biggest advantage, which is speed, the biggest disadvantage is key distribution.

52
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:03,000
But a secondary problem is also this problem of scalability where the keys grow exponentially as you add more people to it.

53
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:09,000
Now there are a number of symmetric algorithms that the industry has come up with.

54
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:14,000
And certainly they all have the same advantages and disadvantages that we just talked about.

55
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:18,000
But some end up being more popular than others.

56
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:23,000
And so for example, DES is still a very popular algorithm that is used out there.

57
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,000
And as you know, the problem with DES is it only supports a 56-bit key,

58
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:34,000
which really today and today's technology makes it insecure because people do have.

59
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:42,000
And certainly companies and organizations do have the ability to be able to brute force that entire key space in a few hours.

60
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:51,000
You know, most of us don't have the infrastructure, the time, the money to be able to build infrastructures that can, for example,

61
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:58,000
brute force 56-bit technology like DES, but certainly companies and other organizations would be able to do that.

62
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:04,000
But knowing that DES was becoming obsolete is something that the industry is known for many years now.

63
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:13,000
And that really led to the development of a other symmetric algorithm called idea that you see here up on your screen.

64
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:19,000
And so what you want to remember about idea is that it's also symmetric, requires the same key at both ends.

65
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:26,000
It's very fast. And it was the first algorithm to use a 128-bit key, for example.

66
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:36,000
So you may need to remember that idea is the first symmetric algorithm to use a key size of 128 bits.

67
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:44,000
Now, there are some other algorithms that exist out there that are not as often used, for example, cast, safer.

68
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:50,000
There's the fish algorithms that exist out there. They all have really advantages and disadvantages.

69
00:06:50,000 --> 00:07:01,000
But the ones that are the most commonly used are still, for example, DES, but used in double DES and triple DES mode that we're going to talk about later on.

70
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:07,000
Now, there is a very popular algorithm that exists out there that is called AES.

71
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:19,000
And the reason it's called AES is because it was the winner of a sponsored competition by the US government called the Advanced Encryption Standard.

72
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:29,000
And what the US government did, realizing that DES was becoming obsolete and DES was used for a lot of applications within the US government.

73
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:37,000
They invited cryptographers around the world to submit their algorithms that could eventually be chosen as a replacement for DES.

74
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And so I think they started off with some 30 odd algorithms that were submitted by people around the world.

75
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:52,000
And slowly, over the span of three or four years, they tested them and slowly waited them down to the best one.

76
00:07:52,000 --> 00:08:01,000
And the best algorithm that was chosen as the winner of this competition was a algorithm that came out of Belgium called Rindall.

77
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:08,000
And so used in a specific way is what the AES algorithm is today.

78
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:17,000
And what's nice about the Rindall algorithm and therefore the AES algorithm is that it's considered to be a variable algorithm.

79
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:27,000
You can choose the key size, you can choose the block size, and you can also choose the number of rounds that it does for substitutions and transpositions.

80
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:40,000
But the AES algorithm supports key sizes of up to 256 bits, which, as you know, is very strong and will be for a long time to come.

81
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:46,000
And so that is becoming a really popular algorithm embedded into all kinds of products.

82
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:51,000
And some of the numbers that you see on the slide here are what you may need to remember.

83
00:08:51,000 --> 00:09:01,000
So for example, the key size in DES is 56, but in the AES algorithm, you know, we can support key lengths of up to 256 bits.

84
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:06,000
There are some other algorithms on here that are symmetric, obviously.

85
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:16,000
The only difference between RC4 that you see on your screen and everything else that's on this slide is that RC4 is a stream cipher,

86
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,000
whereas all of these other algorithms are considered to be block ciphers.

87
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:36,000
And the best algorithms are the ones typically that provide the largest key lengths, and therefore that equates to a larger key space, which makes it stronger against brute force attacks.

88
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:45,000
Now, if you look at any book that's been written about cryptography, or if you see a discussion online, for example,

89
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:53,000
you will typically see a slide that looks like this. And what it is, it's a comparison of strengths of some of these symmetric algorithms.

90
00:09:53,000 --> 00:10:04,000
And the way that you typically read these charts is that anything that supports a key length of less than 80 bits is typically considered to be weak today.

91
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:12,000
And so what we need to use in cryptography applications are really algorithms that are 80 bits and more.

92
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:17,000
And that's why you see, obviously, algorithms like AES be very popular.

93
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:34,000
But cryptologists really agree that anything that's 80 bits and larger typically provides security that is overwhelming and very strong, and really enough for what we are doing today.

94
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:46,000
But still, the most popular algorithms that you see here are DES used in triple DES mode, which really supports a key length as you see here of 168 bits.

95
00:10:46,000 --> 00:11:07,000
But the effective key length, because of something called the meat in the middle attack, reduces its key strength to 112 effective key bit strength, which again is excellent as the cryptologists tell us that anything 80 and above is excellent.

96
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:12,000
But obviously, AES is something that's very popular today as well.

97
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:24,000
You don't have to memorize these numbers, just get a feel for obviously the strongest algorithms like AES and triple DES, for example, as they relate to key strength.

98
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:37,000
Now, we do have to talk a little bit about DES and how obviously it is not something that is considered to be strong enough given the speed of processors today.

99
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:48,000
So our processors are fast enough to be able to brute force that entire key space of DES, 72 quadrillion possible keys, is what it supports.

100
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:53,000
But we have enough technology today to be able to go through that in a few hours.

101
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:05,000
But realizing that DES is one of the best algorithms from a confusion and diffusion perspective, in other words, how it does substitution and transposition is really excellent.

102
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:15,000
The industry has come up with ways to do some creative things with the keys so that it stands up better against brute force attacks.

103
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:20,000
And what they've come up with is double DES and triple DES.

104
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:25,000
Now, double DES simply doubles the keys being used in single DES.

105
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:34,000
So if you take one 56-bit key and you combine it with a second 56-bit key, is really what double DES is.

106
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:38,000
And so now you have a key length that is 112 bits.

107
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:53,000
But there is a specific attack that the industry has come up with called meat in the middle attack that effectively, I mean, the reason it's called meat in the middle attack is because you start at both ends of the key space.

108
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:57,000
You start at key number one and key number 72 quadrillion.

109
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:03,000
And using this specific attack, you start moving towards the middle testing keys.

110
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:09,000
And once you get to the middle, you meat in the middle, you will have found both keys that are being used.

111
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:16,000
And so it turns out that double DES is no more secure than single DES given this meat in the middle attack.

112
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:19,000
And that's why the industry does not use it anymore.

113
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:24,000
It's very difficult to find any specific implementation of double DES.

114
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:27,000
Triple DES, however, is very popular.

115
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:41,000
And as the triple word implies, what we do here is we take either two keys or three keys and use them creatively together to create what triple DES really is.

116
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:51,000
The triple is in reference to not the number of keys that are being used, but the three iterations that triple DES always uses.

117
00:13:51,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And so for example, one of the ways that you could use triple DES in is you have the first key and then the second key and a third different key that will do the encryption.

118
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:14,000
So you can encrypt encrypt with three different keys, for example, but you could also use triple DES with two different keys.

119
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:28,000
I know it sounds a little bit confusing, but really it isn't because if you use two keys and triple DES, what happens is you encrypt with the first key, you encrypt with the second key, and then you encrypt with the first key again.

120
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:41,000
So the reason it's called triple DES is not because of the number of keys that are being used, but the three iterations, for example, encrypt, encrypt, encrypt, that we are doing with the triple DES operations.

121
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:50,000
And it turns out then that the key strength of triple DES is actually 56 times three, which is 168.

122
00:14:50,000 --> 00:15:03,000
Now one of the things that we need to remember here is that same meat in the middle attack that renders double DES, no more secure than single DES can also be applied to triple DES.

123
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:09,000
And just like it does in double DES, it effectively removes 56 bits of strength.

124
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:25,000
But in triple DES, if you're starting with 168 bits of strength, and you can remove 56 bits of strength given the meat in the middle attack, you're still left with 112, which is excellent by today's standards.

125
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:41,000
And that's why even though triple DES is prone to the meat in the middle attack, it's still widely used because effectively it still provides 112 bits of strength, which again is very strong as far as the industry is concerned.

126
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:52,000
Now one algorithm that is very popular and has become very popular over the last number of years is the AES algorithm that we've already talked about.

127
00:15:52,000 --> 00:16:00,000
And as you know, the winner of that AES competition was this algorithm that came out of Belgium called Rindall.

128
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:07,000
And so used in a specific way, for example, is what the AES algorithm actually is.

129
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:12,000
And what you want to remember about the AES algorithm is that it is variable.

130
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:18,000
We can choose the key size, but typically it is used in 256 bit mode.

131
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:25,000
We can choose the number of rounds that it does for simple substitutions and transpositions.

132
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:34,000
And you can also choose the block size that it works because this is also a block symmetric cipher that is used a lot in the industry.

133
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:38,000
I think if you remember those, you'll be just fine.

134
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And so just to summarize how symmetric key cryptography actually works.

135
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:50,000
What we've got here is a nice diagram that I think provides a visual representation of what this looks like.

136
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:57,000
And so if sender and receiver want to be able to communicate using symmetric key cryptography,

137
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:05,000
the sender starts the process by encrypting the message with obviously some symmetric algorithm.

138
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:14,000
And that requires the sender to be able to choose one symmetric key in that entire key space that that specific algorithm supports.

139
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:19,000
And so what they will do is encrypt the message, send it over to the receiver.

140
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:30,000
But the only way that that receiver will be able to decrypt that message is to have the exact same symmetric key to be able to decrypt that message quickly.

141
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:38,000
And so this illustrates the problem that we always have in symmetric key cryptography, which is obviously key distribution.

142
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:47,000
And the book answer to how we get that symmetric key from sender to receiver is out of band.

143
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:59,000
And out of band implies that we use some other channel that is more secure than the channel that we are using for example to communicate the encrypted message in.

144
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:05,000
So the idea is out of band would assume some other method that is much more secure.

145
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:10,000
Those people meet somewhere in between for example, and exchange keys.

146
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:20,000
Now we call this a book answer because in most implementations of cryptography out of band communications is typically not available.

147
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:33,000
Because if some other communications channel is available that counts as out of band, which is more secure than for example what we're communicating to exchange the messages in.

148
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:38,000
Why wouldn't we use that to communicate the secret messages with anyways.

149
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:42,000
And so typically out of band is not available, but it is the book answer.

150
00:18:42,000 --> 00:19:03,000
And again, the perfect definition of out of band means that it is a other communication channel that has more security and that ensures that the keys obviously the symmetric keys will be communicated using a secure channel ensuring that only sender and receiver will have those symmetric keys.

151
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:27,000
And again, the perfect definition of out of band will have those symmetric keys.

